commit_message: Revise so that the text renders well on GitHub.
Check for YAPF only.
Use consistent naming of project.
Add a TravisCI file for continuous integration testing.
Use correct name for README file.
Set the indent to 2.
Use the correct "disable" comment.
Add TravisCI indicator.
Add notice that this isn't an official Google product.
Clarify that YAPF currently requires Python 2.7 and 3.x is planned.
ReST-ify the algorithm description a bit.

ReST-ize the CONTRIBUTING guide

It used to have Markdown markup but without an extension this wasn't rendered by
any tool (including Github). ReST-ize for consistency with the README and since
it's the more common markup format for Python.

Fix default indent_width

Even though it's configurable in style.py, indent_width was stuck to 2 due to
a param of FormatCode. Fix this and add a test that a different indent width
works as well. Command-line tests were modified to make sure that the current
default (4) is actually used when style.py is not mucked with.

Beginnings of Python 3 support.

Add a py3compat module to serve as a compatibility layer for the code, enabling
it to run on both Python 2.7 and 3.4+

All tests except for the actual reformatting pass now (so reformatter_test.py
and yapf_test.py still fail).

Remove another None ~ int comparison.

Trying to format a simple snippet of code now. Remove another instance of a
comparison that gets None < int, which is a type error in Python 3.

Now we're down to the real meat of the porting: unicode/bytes errors.
Add a knob to add a blank line between a class line and the first method.

Add a default value to GetNodeAnnotation

Some node annotations are known to be numeric. For those, it makes sense to have
a default value of 0 when querying, because the result of GetNodeAnnotation is
directly compared with other integers.

Add a default setting and use it everywhere that's relevant.

This lets us pass some reformatting tests on Python 3!

Replace print statement by a print() call.

Using print statements is problematic in formatted code because Python 3
fails in VerifyCode. print() is accepted by both.

Not sure how critical it is to be able to test Python2-style print statements.
If it is, we may want to rig VerifyCode to do a version distinction.

This change lets us pass all reformatter tests on Python 3!

Handle emission to stdout across Python 2 & 3

Also add unit tests for file_resources

Fix Python 3 compatibility issues in the main runner.

All unit tests now pass on Python 2 and Python 3.

commit_message: Adding Python 3.4 testing to Travis CI

Add tests with Python3-specific syntax.

These tests are skipped on Python 2 because VerifyCode will fail after
reformatting.
Update README to mention that Python 3 is now supported.

Move style settings to behind a functional interface.

In preparation for the "big style refactoring". Style settings are now accessed
via .Get calls in the style module rather than reaching out for module
attributes directly.

The global nature of style settings remains untouched. style is accessed
pervasively throughout YAPF - it would be nice to refactor this to pass a style
object through instead; however, that's a separate cleanup.

No change in functionality.

Style refactoring: create distinct PEP8 and Google styles.

Rework style.py to allow creating pre-filled PEP8 (default externally) and
Google styles.

reformatter_test is changed a bit since it was using a messy mixture of styles.
TODO: add some explicit testing for different styles; i.e. instead of just
making indent configurable, test the whole style.
Force 2-space indentation for editing yapf in vim

Style refactoring: Refactor reformatter_test to properly set styles.

Now each TestCase in reformatter_test explicitly sets the style it works with in
setUpClass. _ParseAndUnwrap doesn't need a special indent argument any longer.
By default, most reformatter_test currently tests Google style. Add explicit
tests for the differences in PEP8 style.

Try not to split empty call argument lists.

Or lists with one identifier in them. It makes the code less readable.
Make the use of quotes consistent.
Don't have spaces around the assignments.
Remove unused imports.
Use 'cls', which the linter seems to want.

Add some comments to the docstring.

This satisfies pylint.

Implement configurable styles in yapf.

Idea similar to clang-format: there's a set of supported "known" styles - for
the moment PEP8 and Google. For custom stuff, a configuration file can be
specified.

commit_message: Fix merge issues.
Rename NO_BLANK_LINE_AFTER_CLASS_OR_DEF -> BLANK_LINE_BEFORE_NESTED_CLASS_OR_DEF

Use TestLoader.discover to run all tests in setup.py

Replaces the manual suite() setup in each of the test files. Also doesn't re-run
the blank_line_calculator_test tests.
Document --style and the formatting config file in README.rst
Fix ReST formatting

Beef up README a bit more

* Mention relation to gofmt as well as clang-format
* Mention how to run YAPF without installing
Make errors reading the style config friendlier.
Pass along the 'diff' flag to the formatter.
Enforce a space between 'not' and '('.
Use Google style formatting for consistency.

Make sure we re-add blank lines.

The format snippet will remove all blank lines before it, but we might not want
that.
Disable formatting on hand-formatted data structures.

Run YAPF on the files.

Disable some data literals that were hand formatted.

Run YAPF on files.

No functionality change.
Remove some pylint diagnostics.
gofmt typo

Don't incur a penalty for some splittings.

Splitting before a list comprehension or if-expression shouldn't incur a
penalty. It can lead to more readable code.
Update comment

Add increasingly larger penalties for expressions.

Expressions that are bound more tightly than others will have higher penalties
for splitting.
Run YAPF on itself.
Add yapf entry point to setup.py

Don't set a None SPLIT_PENALTY

The SPLIT_PENALTY annotation must be numeric. Otherwise under Python 3
comparisons to ints will fail.

TODO: need to find other places where SPLIT_PENALTY may be set to None.

Use BOOLEAN_STATES from configparser.

Fixes issue #3.

Refactor CreateStyleFromConfig to split off file reading.

No change in functionality.

Don't recommend to 'sudo install' yapf.

As a matter of fact, it's not our place to tell users how to install Python
packages - users should know that, and everyone should follow her own preferred
way of installing them.

Closes #9

Make sure we have the correct depth.

Compound statements on a single line (e.g., 'while x: a += 1') need to have the
correct line depth for the body of the statement.
Support single line compound stmts for 'elif' and 'else'.

PEP 8 wants two spaces before inline comments.

"Inline comments should be separated by at least two spaces from the
statement."

Update README.rst

Clarify our stance towards PyPI and the status of YAPF in general. Anyone can push a "release" to PyPI, but we don't officially do this at this time.

Separate each item in a list if ends in comma.

If the list ends in a comma, then we place each item on a separate line. This
is one of two ways to help maintain the original intended formatting.

Some cleanups.

* Reformattings,
* Removing terminating spaces,
* Modify some comments.

Opens the README.rst file with an explicit encoding.

This is important because of the difference between bytes and strings
and the follies of `sys.getdefaultencoding()` in guessing the
appropriate encoding. Be explicit; use the utf-8 encoding for the
README.rst file, and decode it explicitly as utf-8-encoded text.

Uses the `codecs.open` function for cross-compatibility between Python 2
and Python 3. In Python 3, `open` takes a keyword argument of
`encoding`, but unfortunately `open` in Python 2 does not. `codecs.open`
solves this issue by taking an explicit encoding as an argument and by
being available in the standard library in both Python 2 and Python 3.
Add reformatting test for a list comprehension

Fix verification when there's a comment between decorators.

Closes #27
Enforce a space after a DOT in import statement.

Ensure that there's a newline at after the code.

The code won't parse if it doesn't end in a newline.
Reformat file with YAPF.

Make sure that we retain the last space.

The last space of a paren level will be lost of the paren stack is popped.
Instead, we set the previous paren last space attribute to the one that's being
popped.
PEP 8 limits column width to 79 characters.

Don't allow a space before a semicolon.

Closes #40

Split semicolon separated statements

Separating statements with a semicolon is discouraged.
yapf_api.ReadFile is not exported, so name it accordingly

Assert minimal supported Python version programmatically

Closes #47

Clarify YAPF's Python 3 vs. 2 runtime requirements.

+minor cosmetic change in README.

Answers #42

Document default style explicitly as pep8.

- Also set it as default in the argument parser (though no functionality changes
here)
- Copy updated usage spew to the README

Closes #34

Use passed-in argv instead of sys.argv in main

Closes #31

Honor ending whitespace after simple statements.

Closes #28

Wrap a single ENDMARKER node in a file_input.

The ENDMARKER might have a comment attached to it. If it's the only node in the
tree, then make sure we wrap it in a "file_input" node so that we won't throw
the comment away.

Closes #41

Add a --noverify flag to yapf and a verify arg to the APIs.

With this flag, YAPF doesn't run the syntax check.

Helps address issues like #42 and #53 to some extent.

Add a test for verification of future imports

Verification will fail, but can be turned off. #53
Rename SingleLineReformatterTest since it's no longer for single lines only

Add tests for stripping blank lines at the end of the file.

Relevant to #25

Support exec used as a method.

Closes #48

A tuple on one line may want to remain on one line.

Improves the affinity for a tuple that's on one contiguous line to not be
split over multiple lines.

Closes #16.

Enforce single line before non-zero column func.

If a function isn't in the 0 column, but isn't in another class or function, it
should still be separated by a single blank line, not two. This is a bit of a
grey area in the style guide, but other tools seem to expect this.

Closes #24

Don't split keyword/argument pairs.

Retain things like this:

  self.foo(aaaaaaaaaaaa=bbbbbbbbbbbbbbbb, cccccccccccccc=ddddddddddd, ...)

Not only does this violate the style guide, it lowers readability.

Closes #29.

Add an example of formatting done by YAPF.

Closes #13

Add space between ending comma and closing bracket

Add a knob to specify if we want a space between the ending comma and closting
bracket.

Closing #20

Update example to be PEP 8 compliant.

Also random other reformattings.
Add section on disabling YAPF formatting.

Try to maintain the original formatting.

If the "trailer" was on a single line, then let's try to keep it on that line.

Closes #12.
Change verifier to raise InternalError when normalization fails.

Disable post-reformatting verification by default.

Changes the --noverify flag to be --verify, which is false by default.
Add conversion for style element.

Remove references to "verifying" code.

The flag is disabled by default and used only for development purposes.
Reformat using YAPF.
Prefer not to split before the ending paren of an if statement.
Reformat with YAPF.

Add support for line continuations.

If we encounter a line continuation, we make an assumption that the programmer
knew what they were doing and then we leave the line alone. Failing to do so
could lead to syntactically correct, but semantically wrong code.

Address feedback.

Add some more tests for continuation markers.
Use the correct indentation for closing brackets.

Improve how lines are enabled or disabled.

Disable them during reformatting. This allows us to still correct indentations
while not formatting the code.

Add test case for #36.

Closes #36.
Keep empty containers from splitting if we can.
Expose API to external applications.

Expand the style syntax to specify on command line

Using the syntax:

  --syntax='{based_on_style: foo, bar: 42, baz: qux}'

The user can now create a style based on another style and modify it to
their liking from the command line.
Cleanup some pylint diagnistic messages.
Add example of config dictionary for the --style flag.
fix "manifold"->"many-fold" typo

Allow files in any position.

This lets the user do things like:

  yapf file1.py file2.py --style='{based_on_style: pep8, column_limit: 100}'

Split strings only when surrounded by brackets

Closes #65

Retain vertical spacing

The vertical spacing should be retained if we are formatting only specific lines.

Closes #66
add version cli argument
use setuptools (otherwise entry_points is ignored)
It's Horizontal, not Vertical
Retain vertical whitespace between formatted lines
Retain vert spacing between enable/disable regions.

Ending whitespace in comments.

Retain the ending whitespace if we're ignoring those lines and remove them
otherwise.
Add coverage support.
Fix URL.
Use correct value for install section.
Update the URL for coveralls.
Add coverage support.

Bump required Python 3.4 version to 3.4.1

lib2to3 in 3.4.1 learns to recognize "yield from"

See #61 and others.

Wrap elements after a percent expression.

Closes #69.

Allow "builder" style function calls.

A '.NAME' may be part of a builder call. E.g.:

  obj = (builder
         .add_foo()
         .add_bar()
         .add_baz())
Exclude verifier.py from coverage analysis.
Add a bare bones VIM plugin script for YAPF.
Remove absolute paths so the user can change them
Remove lint warnings.
Reformat via YAPF.

Fix testing errors on Python 3.4

The SPLIT_PENALTY annotation must be numeric! Python 3 disallows comparing None
with integers.

Adding yapftests to packages in setup.py

This enables running tests after installing yapf from sdist

Bump version to 0.1.3

This is the first uploaded version to PyPI

Mention PyPI in the README

similar to #11

Bump version to 0.1.4

PyPI wouldn't let reuploading the same version

Adding some documentation on hacking on yapf

Currently info on releases
Update .gitignore to include build/sdist artifacts
Update to reflect pypi installtion.
fix #74, --lines over multiline strings erroneously inserted newlines

Improve handling of filenames on the command line

Don't call GetCommandLineFiles unless there are positional
arguments (args.files), and only pass the positional parameters
(otherwise GetCommandLineFiles ends up processing all the args
as well).

Prior to this change if you run 'yapf -i foo.c' it will give you
the unhelpful error:
'cannot use --in_place or --diff flags when reading from stdin'

Add a unit test for this case. Would add here but would prefer
to use 'mock' and don't see a dependency on 'mock' yet.

Also, give a useful error message when positional paramters
are specified but not arguments were given.

Add README to plugins directory to explain usage.

This is just the beginning. As more IDEs get plugins, this will be extended a
lot.
Add PyPI version badge.
Add testcase for "star_expr".

Add .coverage to .gitignore

This file is generated by the 'coverage' tool.

Also, add / to beginning of entries that should only
be ignored in the root of the repo.

Update YAPF style guide in CONTRIBUTING.rst

Also wrap long line in README.rst.

Retain formatting of multiline shebang.

The formatting of a multiline shebang shouldn't be touched. Otherwise, it could
screw up the syntax of the shell script.

Closes #78.

Align closing bracket with visual indent

PEP 8 requires aligning the closing bracket with the visual indentation.
Update HACKING guide to test pip installs

Use utf-8 instead of unicode_escape when forcing encoding.

unicode_escape messes up escaped chars in strings. We'll assume we're
interacting with valid utf-8-encoded strings.

Closes #70
Closes #79

Banish TAB-related settings: they are dead code

The USE_TAB and TAB_WIDTH settings aren't being used, and they are an eye sore;
yapf doesn't support tabs at this time, and we don't really plan to in the near
future, so it's a shame to have dead code that just confuses users.

Closes #63

Include decorators when figuring out blank lines.

Closes #23.

Add a "chromium" style.

YAPF is more closely related to the Chromium Python style. It conflicts with
the external Google style in a few key ways. So create a Chromium style and
have YAPF use that.

Closes #83

When we have a continuation, retain newlines.

If we don't retain the newlines, then comments may be "inlined" into the code,
which results in most of the code being commented out.

Closes #76
Retain semicolons when not formatting its line.
Honour disable/enable comments when --lines is set

Take multiline strings into account.

When we disable a region, we want to take multiline strings into account before
saying we need a newline.
Bump up version number.
Clear out the buffer before replacing it.
Fix typo in contributor guidelines
add --style-help cli, show style's settings and setting docstrings
add tox.ini file, for py27 and py34
Cosmetic cleanup
remove py32 and py33 from supported versions in setup.py

Try not to split around a term operator.

Closes #92

Increase penalty for splitting in a subscript list

Closes #95.

fix .travis.yml, report a failure if the tests fail

setup.py test should return non-zero exit code if there's a test failure

Raise a SyntaxError when passed bad syntax.

Prior to this change, bad syntax would raise a ParseError which wasn't very
descriptive. This also inserts the filename into the exception message
so it's clear where the bad syntax was.

File "bad.py", line 1
  a = 42
  ^
IndentationError: unexpected indent

Split list with interspersed comments.

Add a heuristic that will place individual items in a list on separate lines if
there are interspersed comments.

Open files with an encoding.

If we don't open files with the correct encoding, it will lose information when
reading and writing the files. In particular, if there's a byte order mark
(BOM), then it will not detect it, which causes an error to occur in the
parsing. And then when we write the file, that BOM is lost.

Closes #50
Bump version to 0.1.6.
Remove dead properties on format_token.
Add Emacs plugin installation directions

Add tests for stdin, --style-help and --version.

Increases test coverage.

...because context managers.

Run yapf on all files.

Rename patch_input to patched_input (in main_test).
Remove some lint warnings.

Add wheels to the release strategy.

For more details see:

- http://wheel.readthedocs.org/en/latest/
- https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0427/
- http://lucumr.pocoo.org/2014/1/27/python-on-wheels/

Mark a list comprehension's subtype.

We don't want a penalty for splitting before a list comp's 'for' or 'if'
statements.

Revert "Mark a list comprehension's subtype."

This reverts commit c75595059d11c764c977fdccd1cfe1e624d232b6.
Allow easy splitting before comp list fors and ifs.
Fix spelling error, "refomatted" -> "reformatted"

Fix edge case of python file which is blank lines.

Before this was just passed through (no diff was shown,
nothing happened inplace)

Up the excess character penalty.

Going over by one character should cause the formatter to reject it except in
extreme circumstances.
Ensure unicode literals in python 2.

Raise the exception even if we have a logger.

Otherwise, the error returned will be meaningless.

Allow formatting Python files without .py suffix.

Closes #126
Check that the encoding is actually correct.
Bump up version number to 0.1.7.

Add docs on how to run YAPF on itself

Ideally we should also provide a tools (or docs) on how
to run YAPF on the just the parts of the file changes
on a git branch (a la chromium's 'git cl format').

Add support for project-local style (in .style.yapf)

YAPF will now look for this file at startup and use it as
the default if found.  If not found pep8 is still the default.

Now that we have project-local style there is no need for the
hardcoded yapf style (it will be the default for all files
in the yapf tree now).
Replacing tox.ini syntax that doesn't work on some tox versions.
Fix grammar in HACKING.rst
Increase test coverage of file_resources

Don't print backtraces for user/input errors

This change introduces a common YapfError parent class
that can be used for input/user error.  run_main() then
handles these errors and prints a nice error message
rather than a nasty backtrace (backtraces IMHO should
only be printed for program errors).

Fixes #130

Add better assert message when formatter tests fail

The output of self.assertEqual is very hard to read
for code comparison. Add self.assertCodeEqual which
prints the expected and actual code in an easy to
read way.

commit_message: Bump up version to 0.1.8.
Reformat to remove lint warnings.

Add a newline if the original list had a newline.

To help retain the original hand-formatted code, enforce a newline after an
opening brace (and before the closing brace) if there was one in the original
code.

commit_message: Add a newline before a comment on a separate line.

Remove dead code.

The stack should never be empty.
Add test to improve coverage.
Align concatenated strings together in dicts.
Allow a space between a comma and colon.
Use parentheses for print for 3.0 compat.

Force subtyping of certain subtypes.

Some subtypes may be overridden, but are important to retain because of future
formatting decisions.

Closes #143

Unary 'not' is now less likely to be split after

Closes #89
Bump up version to 0.1.9.

Don't modify horizontal spaces when disabled.

Closes #146, #147

Remove code that doesn't have any effect.

The code that's supposed to keep a subscript region together doesn't
seem to have much effect on the generated code. This needs to be
reworked. But remove it for now to fix #30.

Closes #30
Remove stale reference to deleted var.
Fixing #issue89 and chaging the test to dont override any function
Added sublime text to plugin readme (see issue #151)
Bump version to 0.2.0
- fixed infinite regression for .style search on windows filesystems

Add how to use as module to the README

Fix #148

Add in_place argument to FormatFile.

(For use as a module.)

Corrects the docstring of FormatCode to say that it raises if there is an
IOError. Previously this claimed it returned (None, encoding) which was
not correct. Now (None, encoding) is used if the FormatFile was used with
in_place.

Mention FormatFile's in_place argument in readme.

Also fix a typo from updating the README in #157.

Note: in_place argument introduced in #158.
Fix function call formatting inside of dicts
Bump up version to 0.2.1
Fix all lint warnings.
Fixes function call formatting when dictionaries are nested

Don't break after a 'not'.

Closes #167.

Make sure we abort loop when there isn't a basename

Closes #159.

DOC: Use a valid literal in README

Switch example from using a set of lists (which is invalid because python lists are mutable and hence not hashable) to a set of tuples.
Remove impossible situations.
Make the logger a parameter.

Add test of column limit.

Don't merge lines that go over the column limit.
Increase coverage testing.

Allow splitting after a ':'.

However, we don't allow splitting after the ':' of a lambda expression.

Distinguish continuation line from next line.

An 'if' statement's expression may align to the body of the if statement
if we have 4-space indentations. Make sure that we don't do that by
over indenting the continuation line.

Closes #21
Increase penalty for going over column limit

Emit unformatted line if no formatting found

The formatter will barf out the line without whitespaces, causing invalid
lines, etc. Instead, emit the line unformatted.
Remove lint warnings.
Update version to 0.2.2.

Retain ending comments.

If a comment happens at the end of a line, we assume that it's there for a
reason. E.g., a "pylint: disable" comment will normally go over the column
limit.

Closes #124
Retian horizontal space with continuations.

Retain horizontal spaces.

Make sure that the original column of a disabled bit of code is retained.

Closes #94

Don't over indent function call arguments.

Closes #170.
Remove unused variable.

Increase the penalty for splitting after unary ops.

Seriously, that shit shouldn't happen.
Update to version 0.2.3.

Retain spaces after a multiline string.

Closes #173

Don't add spaces around keyword-default pairs.

No really this time. This modifies how "subtypes" are kept on nodes. It allows
them to be a set of values instead of just one.

Closes #174
Update to version 0.2.4.

Remove code that didn't add much value.

The value of the splitting before the closing brace decision code wasn't used
much. There are better ways to achieve this.

Don't split before the closing subscript bracket.

Closes #169.
Fix indentation.
Update to version 0.2.5.

Brutally enforce splitting with named args.

If we have default values or named args, then people seem to *really*
want to split *all* arguments instead of bin packing some of them.
Handle disable/enable as part of a multiline comment.
Fix lint issues.
Try not to split single function arguments.
Bump version to v0.2.6

Retain vert spacing inside data literals.

Closes #180
Add option to not join lines.
Use correct escaping.
Fix test.
Bump version to v0.2.7
Return 1 if the source code changed.
Honor splitting before or after logical ops.
Retain comment position when formatting is disabled.
Prefer to split before bitwise operators.
Strongly connect closing paren to parameter list
Split only at start of named assign.
Update ChangeLog with commits since v0.2.7.
Retain spacing between disabled and enabled lines.
Fix change log to be more comprehensible.
Update version to v0.2.8.

Fix formatting of multiple files

FormatFiles was returning after formatting the first file, even if
multiple files were provided.
Update to v0.2.9.
Return '2' on error.

Return '2' if the source changed.

Python seems to return '1' if an exception occurred.

Closes #186
Correct expected return code.
Format when lines are specified in middle of expression.
Correct naming of command line option.
Update to v0.3.0

Use the proper column for closing scope indent.

The "column" field on the format_token is the original column from the lib2to3
parser. This won't be correct for reformatting the closing scope bracket if the
indentation size changes. Instead use the column that's being calculated.

Closes #188
Bump version to v0.3.1

Reset previous column for a multiline string.

The multiline string's previous starting column is '0' if we are processing a
multistring.

Add DEDENT_CLOSING_BRACKETS

This allows for PEP8-compatible JSON-style scope organization that has the
following properties:

* produces smaller diffs
* uniformly treats all closing brackets, including function definitions,
  calls and data structures
* leaves more space on the line by solving the PEP8 violation known as
  "continuation line with same indent as next logical line" without
  additional indentation

commit_message: Update for 0.4.0 release.

Don't over indent when line can be distinguished.

Closes #181

Add a flag to exclude files & dirs from formatting

Closes #128

Allow sensible splitting of array elements.

Closes #111

Add a knob SPLIT_PENALTY_IMPORT_NAMES

This controls whether an import statement that goes over 80 columns will begin
on the same line as the '(' or start on the following line.

Closes #84
Correct formatting of style help output.
Strongly connect the ending bracket to the atom.
Enforce use of spaces required for disabled lines
Update for v0.5.0 release.

Use the longest dict entry instead of total dict length.

When determining if we should split a dictionary's value to a new line, use the
longest entry instead of the total dictionary's length. This allows the
formatter to reformat the dictionary in a more consistent manner.

Use the longest dict entry instead of total dict length.

When determining if we should split a dictionary's value to a new line, use the
longest entry instead of the total dictionary's length. This allows the
formatter to reformat the dictionary in a more consistent manner.

Graduate to "Beta".

Also reformat so that it's <80 columns.

Improve how list comprehensions are formatted.

Make splitting dependent upon whether the "comp_for" or "comp_if" goes over the
column limit.
Over indent only when we don't dedent bracket

Split when first argument is a func call with args

Improve splitting heuristic when the first argument to a function call
is itself a function call with arguments. In cases like this, the
remaining arguments to the function call would look badly aligned, even
though they are techincally correct (the best kind of correct!).

Add knob to indent the dictionary value

The Chromium style requires the dictionary value be indented on the new line.

Split before data literal in arg list.

If the first argument in a function call and its length goes over the column
limit, then we want to split before it so that we won't mess up the rest of the
arguments' formatting.
Remove spaces around '**' operator.
Don't assing subtypes to all dict value elements.

Add pseudo parentheses around dict vals

This allows us to reformat as if the dictionary value was surrounded by
parentheses, which is desirable for some style guides.

Retain formatting of comments in an expr.

If a comment comes in the middle of an unwrapped line (like an if
conditional with comments interspersed), then we want to split if the
original comments were on a separate line.

Reformat with YAPF.

Eating our own dogfood. :-)

commit_message:
Modify how python files are identified.

- No longer check that a file is a "Python" file unless the '--recursive' flag
  is specified.
- No longer allow the user to specify a directory unless the '--recursive' flag
  is specified.

Remove unneeded method.

The only nodes passed in were pytree.Leaf nodes. So simplify and inline the
method.
Add check for disabled semicolon separated stmts.

However, this could result in bad looking code if the call could be placed on
one line. I.e., there are two or three arguments. Therefore, try not to split
in these situations.

Stablize reformatting with Facebook style

The line number cannot be used to determine if the line should be split when
"dedenting" is specified. The reason for this is because a newline may be added
without splitting around the brackets. Then if we rerun yapf on the output, the
code will be on different lines, and therefore be formatted again.

This change doesn't rely upon the token's original line number.

commit_message:
Don't count closing scopes

When we determine if the scope is the last scope on the line, we shouldn't
count a closing scope token. Just looking at the opening one should suffice.

Closes #254
Bump up version to 0.8.2
Add 2016 to the copyright dates
Don't split before a first element list arg
Don't penalize when the line must be split
Calculate the length from the correct ending token
If the last scope in line, just use matching bracket
Specify if the line must be split
Don't give extra penalties for a must split

Determine if the opening bracket was split

This heuristic is only partially correct. It uses the opening bracket's column
in the unformatted source to determine if it was split when looking at the
closing bracket. This is because there's no way in yapf to determine if a token
is going to be split in the final output until the final line is reconstructed.

Add a knob for splitting before an if expr

Closes #255

Allow splitting before single argument

A function call with a single argument can be split before that
argument. This prevents splitting in bad places, like before the ending
brackets of a list or something.

If the argument / parameter list is going to be split, then encourage
splitting before the first argument.

lib2to3 places logically different comments into the same DEDENT in some
instances. Detect this and separate them as best as we can.

Split after an opening bracket if named assigns

When we intentionally split each argument because of a named assignment, then
also split after the opening bracket (before the first argument). This makes
things a bit nicer to look at. It also allows one to rename the function
without having to reformat all of the arguments to the function call.

Fix some pylint warnings

Refactor the parsing and checking test code
Clean up some imports and formatting
Specify a "comp_op" as a binary operator.

Encompass the dictionary value in pseudo parens

If a dictionary's value has a comment before it, then we want to include the
value within the pseudo parens. Otherwise only the comment is seen as being
part of the dictionary's value.
Pseudo-parentheses have no length.

A dictionary entry doesn't count

Ignore dictionary entries in dictionaries when determining if each
dictionary entry can fit on single lines. If one can't, it looks better
not to split because the dictionary entry would split nicely anyway.
Using concurrent.futures to format multiple files at the same time
Fix lint warnings.
Don't count pseudo-parens in the length of the line.
Bump version to v0.14.0

Don't count comments for dict entries

Comments aren't part of a dictionary key, so it shouldn't be counted when
looking at the length of an entry.

Allow text before 'pylint' comments.

b/32567870
Allow text before a 'yapf:' comment
Fix some formatting issues.

Add handling for unpacking with dict expressions

Only works on Python 3.6, since lib2to3 in Python 3.5 fails to work
with with PEP448 unpacking syntax.
Make travis build 3.6 as well, plus handle versions beyond 3.6
Align with project code style
Keep type annotations intact if possible

No space after type hint

Closes #351

Distinguish decorator '@' from matrix mult.

Closes #350

Split at beginning of list instead of later.

This is done when the formatter has to decide such things as whether it should
split at the beginning of the list or, say, and empty list. We prefer the
former in this situation.
Bump up year in copyright statement
Bump to v0.15.1

Don't split too aggressively with named assigns

If a function call that has a named assign is part of an argument list,
don't cause the other arguments to split just because it has a named
assign. I.e., 'a' won't be forced to split here:

  func(a, b, c, d(x, y, z=42))

Allow subscript splitting around and/or ops

The LHS and RHS of the ops are still left contiguous, but loosen the
restriction when it's and/or ops.

Closes #332

Suggestion: VIM command

I do not use YAPF so often, so I do not want a mapping. But calling the function is unhandy, too. Therefore I created a VIM command `:YAPF` that can take a range (see comments in code for how to use it).
Bump to v0.15.2
Remove superfluous parentheses
Remove some pylint warnings.

Add two knobs for formatting dictionaries and sets

- The EACH_DICT_ENTRY_ON_SEPARATE_LINE knob places each dict entry on separate
  lines if the full dictionary can't fit on a single line.
- The `SPLIT_BEFORE_DICT_SET_GENERATOR` knob splits before the `for` part of a
  dict/set generator.
Don't print trailing white space with --style-help.

Add converters for new knobs

Also reorder so that they're alphabetical.

Noticed by @kobras8

Split comma-term dict/set and list makers

If there's a comma-terminated dict/set or list maker, then ensure a split even
if there's only one entry.

Add blank line before class's docstring.

Closes #358

alternative standard libarary 'tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile' which sadly
dosn't do what one would want. Utils also provides 'TempFileContents'
and 'stdout_redirectory'.

commit_message:
Python 2 standard/file output fixes.

WriteReformattedCode would do newline transformation even though that
step has been manually taken care of before that point.
It is more of a coincident that the would not happen on python 2.

py3compat.EncodeAndWriteToStdout will now on Python 2 try to set the
windows stdout to O_BINARY mode before outputting. Otherwise newline
transformation would occur.
NamedTempFile support for python 3<..<=3.4
Simplify utils.py:NamedTempFile to one version
Document Python 2 fixes to stdout

Add ALLOW_MULTILINE_DICTIONARY_KEYS knob

This allows us to split a dictionary key over multiple lines, which is
something pylint doesn't like.

Using the original formatting makes yapf non-stable in many cases when
formatting the exact same code.

this whitespace being wasted.

              yyy='another long string',

Update PEP 8 style to match modern PEP 8

PEP 8 was updated last year to prefer that line splits come before binary operators, rather than after:

https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#should-a-line-break-before-or-after-a-binary-operator
https://github.com/python/peps/commit/c59c4376ad233a62ca4b3a6060c81368bd21e85b

Really there should be a way to do this for other binary operations... for example, even with this setting, YAPF wants to do:

```
     orig_extracted = (
-        extract_tb(orig.__traceback__)
-        + extract_tb(orig.exceptions[0].__traceback__)
-        + extract_tb(orig.exceptions[0].exceptions[1].__traceback__))
+        extract_tb(orig.__traceback__) +
+        extract_tb(orig.exceptions[0].__traceback__) +
+        extract_tb(orig.exceptions[0].exceptions[1].__traceback__))
```

which is exactly what the example in PEP 8 says not to do. But this patch brings YAPF's PEP 8 style closer to what PEP 8 says.

Make async formatting more intelligent

Before Python 3.5, async was not a keyword. The formatting of Python 2
code that uses async as a module name, for example, should not treat

Use a TextIOWrapper when reading from stdin.

Some systems may have different encodings (e.g., CP936 for Windows). In those
cases, using "input()" doesn't work if the text isn't ASCII. Using an IO
wrapper handles this.

Closes #449

Fix split penalty for single-argument function calls with generators.

The previous logic retained the normal penalty for splitting before the
only argument of a function call when that argument was a generator
expression such as 'f(a for a in x)'. This caused formatting
irregularities where generators were squeezed towards the end of the
line instead of being reflowed onto the next one.

This change removes those penalties so that single-argument generators
are considered normal function arguments.

Improve formatting on list/dict/set comprehensions.

Terminology reference:
    [loop_var for loop_var in a_list if loop_var]
     ^      ^ ^                    ^ ^         ^
     \-expr-/ \------comp_for------/ \-comp_if-/

Implements the following preferences:
- Try to keep comprehensions on a single line.
- Prefer splitting at comp_if when comp_for was split as well.
- Try to avoid splitting at comp_for when expr exactly matches the loop
  variable.
  - This keeps the (often short) clauses together: [a for a in ...].

    for var in sorted(looooooooooooooooooong)

pretty strong bias towards keeping everything on the same line (but not
too strong that it upsets common cases).

80 might be too high for PEP8 but I think 0 penalty results in some
pretty lousy formatting.

commit_message: Grammatical tweak
Bump version to v0.20.0
Default 'verify' to False.
Update vim plugin instructions.

Flip INDENT_DICTIONARY_VALUE for Facebook style

With INDENT_DICTIONARY_VALUE=False the dictionaries with long values are formatted in a very bad way

`cat test.py`

    conf = {
        'first_key': True,
        'second_key': [],
        'third_key': 'Beautiful is better than ugly.'
                     'Explicit is better than implicit.'
                     'Simple is better than complex.'
                     'Complex is better than complicated.'
    }

`cat style.yapf`

    [style]
    BASED_ON_STYLE=pep8

`yapf test.py`

    conf = {
        'first_key':
        True,
        'second_key': [],
        'third_key':
        'Beautiful is better than ugly.'
        'Explicit is better than implicit.'
        'Simple is better than complex.'
        'Complex is better than complicated.'
    }

Notice how the first key/value pair is split into two lines, while the second key/value pair is not. While it's somewhat understandable the way the third key/value pair is treated, there's no sensible way to explain the splitting the first key/value pair.

Now when you flip INDENT_DICTIONARY_VALUE:

`cat style.yapf`

    [style]
    BASED_ON_STYLE=pep8
    INDENT_DICTIONARY_VALUE=True

`yapf test.py`

    conf = {
        'first_key': True,
        'second_key': [],
        'third_key': 'Beautiful is better than ugly.'
                     'Explicit is better than implicit.'
                     'Simple is better than complex.'
                     'Complex is better than complicated.'
    }

Much better isn't it?

Fix checking for 'async def'

Fix formatting with use_tabs=True.

There are two issues when setting use_tabs=True:

1) The indent_width then makes no sense as a single tab per indentation is
   always desired.

2) Aligning things vertically after the indentation should never be done with
   tabs. The current setting assumes that a tab has the same width as a a single
   space and breaks the following code spectacularly:

def test():
	my_module.call_function("1234567890", "1234567890", "1234567890", "1234567890", "1234567890")

For example, clang-format still uses spaces for vertical alignment when using
tabs for indentation.

commit_message:
Keep comments attached to prev objects.

A comment may be in the "prefix" of a pytree node, but is actually attached to
the object before the node. E.g., if the node is a function or class, we don't
want to comment to appear to be attached to it instead of the original object.

http://google.github.io/styleguide/pyguide.html#34-indentation

Adjust newlines if nested class/func

Closes #645

Add knob SPLIT_ALL_TOP_LEVEL_COMMA_SEPARATED_VALUES (#1)

Add knob SPLIT_ALL_TOP_LEVEL_COMMA_SEPARATED_VALUES

The existing knob SPLIT_ALL_COMMA_SEPARATED_VALUES is overly aggresive in that, if an argument list (or, more generally, a container) needs splitting, then all subexpressions will be split as well. For instance, in
```
abcdef(aReallyLongThing, b=(c,d))
```
if the line needs splitting because of `aReallyLongThing`, then it will produce
```
abcdef(
    aReallyLongThing,
    b=(c,
       d))
```
I've seen terrible things like
```
   argument: [Int,
              Int]
```
in function definitions with many arguments (even if the second `Int` fits in the line).

The new knob checks if a container (argument list, list literal, etc) fits in a line and avoids breaking if so, producing
```
abcdef(
    aReallyLongThing,
    b=(c, d))
```
which makes more sense (to me at least).

See https://github.com/prodo-ai/plz/pull/248 for an example of a codebase reformatted with the new knob (plus  `split_before_first_argument`). Nice, isn't it?

Add space inside brackets

For issue #811, add a style option "SPACE_INSIDE_BRACKETS".

``SPACE_INSIDE_BRACKETS``
    Use spaces inside brackets and parens.  For example:

    .. code-block:: python

        method_call( 1 )
        my_dict[ 3 ][ 1 ][ get_index( *args, **kwargs ) ]
        my_set = { 1, 2, 3 }

This Bool option (False by default) inserts spaces after opening, and
before closing brackets (parens, brackets, and braces, to be precise).

Use spaces around the subscript / slice operator.  For example:

they're used as a subscript / slice operator.

Allow `lines` parameter to fix whitespace between statements. (#864)

* Fix split penalty for single-argument function calls with generators.

The previous logic considered all components of the generator in a
single-argument call such as 'f(a for a in x)' to be strongly connected
like a normal single-argument call (e.g. 'f(a_var)'). This caused
formatting irregularities in these cases.

This change retains normal split penalties in the single-argument
generator case.

* Allow `lines` parameter to fix whitespace between statements.

The previous logic largely ignored `lines` values that were not part of
statements. This means that yapf required a statement to be formatted to
make whitespace-only changes.

This logic tweak allows `lines` to be taken into account even when the
adjacent statements are disabled (i.e. not in `lines`).

pylint and pytype end of line comments adjusting their behavior are
already handled specially.  This does the same for copybara.

I don't like that this is turning into a chain of property calls,
refactoring this into a single question of "is this end of line comment

pushing internally maintained code to upstream to keep internal
google-isms from escaping.

Elaborate on based_on_style origins and use cases. (#896)

Several Google OSS projects I have contributed to have mistakenly assumed that they should use
the `"google"` style with `indent_width` manually set to `2`. Since Google does not follow the 
(public) Google Python Style Guide however, this creates numerous diffs between the internal 
formatter and `yapf --style=google`.

`yapf --style=yapf` does not perfectly match the internal formatter (e.g. for docstrings),
but it is much closer than `yapf --style={based_on_style: google, indent_width: 2}`,
particularly since it sets `SPLIT_BEFORE_EXPRESSION_AFTER_OPENING_PAREN=True`.
